3. Network Drivers

Docker supports several network drivers.

Driver	Purpose	Use Case
bridge	Default	Containers on same host
host	Shares host network	High performance
none	No networking	Complete isolation
overlay	Multiple Docker hosts	Swarm/Kubernetes
macvlan	Container gets physical IP	Legacy applications
ipvlan	Similar to macvlan	Advanced networking
4. Bridge Network (Default)

Most commonly used.

When Docker is installed:

docker network ls

Output:

NETWORK ID     NAME      DRIVER
12aa34bc       bridge    bridge
23ab45cd       host      host
45bc56de       none      null

Bridge network is automatically created.

Architecture

docker0 Bridge

          |
----------------------------
|            |            |
Container1 Container2 Container3
172.17.0.2 172.17.0.3 172.17.0.4

Each container gets an IP.

Example

Run container

docker run -dit --name web nginx

Check IP

docker inspect web

or

docker inspect -f '{{range.NetworkSettings.Networks}}{{.IPAddress}}{{end}}' web

Output

172.17.0.2
5. User-defined Bridge Network

Recommended over the default bridge.

Create

docker network create mynetwork

Check

docker network ls

Run containers

docker run -dit --name app1 --network mynetwork nginx

docker run -dit --name app2 --network mynetwork nginx

Now they can communicate using names.

app1
 |
 |-------> app2

Test

docker exec -it app1 ping app2

No IP required.

Docker DNS resolves names automatically.

